--- body ---
## Context

`/pick-ticket` re-reads and re-assesses every open ticket from scratch on every
beat. For each candidate it checks scope, reads the `## Attempt log`, applies
exclusion rules, and ranks — all from cold. With many tickets this is wasteful
and grows linearly.

The fix is to make assessment incremental: cache the picker's per-ticket verdict
in the ticket's own log section so a future beat can fast-path past tickets whose
inputs haven't changed.

No separate index file. The ticket log is the right place — it's append-only,
committed, and already used for attempt outcomes.

Where this logic belongs (beat.py vs. pick-ticket skill) is an open design
question. The ticket does not prescribe it; the implementer should decide during
planning.

## Actions

1. Define a new log verb (or reuse `note`) for picker assessments, e.g.:
   `{ts} claude note sweep-skip: {reason} expires:{date}`
   or a dedicated verb `assessed` if the FORMAT.md closed set is extended.

2. In the picker, after applying exclusion rules to a candidate:
   - If excluding, append `sweep-skip` with the reason and a TTL (e.g. 24 h for
     scope-too-large, 1 h for 24h-cooldown).
   - On the next beat, read existing `sweep-skip` lines. If the most recent one
     is within its TTL and the ticket body/status hasn't changed since, skip
     re-assessment.

3. For the selected ticket (PICK), append a `note sweep-pick` line so the
   attempt log records the selection event separately from the outcome.

4. Update FORMAT.md or `harness-rules/tickets.md` if a new verb is added.

## Test

- Ticket with a valid unexpired `sweep-skip` line: picker skips without
  re-reading the body or running scope estimation.
- Ticket with an expired `sweep-skip` line: picker re-assesses.
- Ticket body changes after a `sweep-skip` line: picker re-assesses regardless
  of TTL.

## Exit criteria

- A ticket excluded by the picker has a log line recording why and when.
- A subsequent beat run skips re-assessment of that ticket if within TTL and
  body unchanged.
- The selected ticket has a `sweep-pick` (or equivalent) log line.
- No separate index file is created.
- FORMAT.md (or tickets harness rule) reflects any new verb.
